---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Prose from "../components/Prose.astro";

const experience = [
  {
    role: "Manager, Project Development",
    company: "Railinc Corp.",
    period: "Oct 2024 — Present",
    location: "Cary, NC",
  },
  {
    role: "Full Stack Software Engineer",
    company: "Clinetic",
    period: "Mar 2021 — Jun 2024",
    location: "Raleigh-Durham, NC",
  },
  {
    role: "Senior Software Engineer",
    company: "Harvested Financial",
    period: "Jun 2020 — Mar 2021",
    location: "",
  },
  {
    role: "Software Engineer",
    company: "Galatea Associates",
    period: "Apr 2018 — Jun 2020",
    location: "Greater Boston",
  },
  {
    role: "Financial Advisor",
    company: "Voya Financial Advisors",
    period: "Sep 2015 — Apr 2018",
    location: "Raleigh-Durham, NC",
  },
  {
    role: "Workplace Planning & Guidance Consultant",
    company: "Fidelity Investments",
    period: "Aug 2014 — Aug 2015",
    location: "",
  },
];

const certifications = [
  "Project Management Professional (PMP)",
  "AWS Essential Training for Developers",
  "Learning Spring 6 with Spring Boot 3",
  "Series 7 (expired in 2019)",
  "Series 66 (expired in 2019)",
  "Life, Health, Long Term Care Insurance (expired in 2020)"
];
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Hunter Motte — Engineering Manager at Railinc Corp. The longer story behind the homepage."
>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 sm:px-8 pt-12 sm:pt-16">
    <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl leading-[1.05] tracking-tight">
      The longer story.
    </h1>
  </section>

  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 sm:px-8 mt-14">
    <Prose>
      <h2>How I got here</h2>
      <p>
        Coming out of college at UNC, I was not 100% sure about what I wanted to do.
        I landed at Fidelity Investments and got my Series 7 and Series 66 licenses to
        deliver Fidelity 401(k) customers with investment guidance. After having those
        conversations with customers on the phone, I wanted to do the same thing but in-person.
        I joined Voya Financial as an independent Financial Advisor and worked with Wake County Public School System
        staff, since Voya held their 403(b) plan. I came to understand the NC Pension system and various challenges our
        educators face when planning for retirement.
      </p>
      <p>
        In 2017, I started to question what I REALLY wanted to do in life. Working on building something from scratch
        always interested me, and at this time I was following all the happenings in Silicon Valley. The
        idea of learning how to code so I could build something of my own consumed me. I started with free resources
        like Codecademy and freeCodeCamp.org so see if I was interested in coding. I caught the bug instantly and
        decided to pursue software development as a career by going through a formal bootcamp. While working my existing
        job as a Financial Advisor, I completed the bootcamp and built projects on nights and weekends and eventually landed a software role
         in finance in Boston.
      </p>
      <p>
          That role started my journey as a Software Engineer. I was fortunate to work with great coworkers at Galatea Associates
          with great clients working on very interesting financial software projects. I eventually decided to try my hand in the startup
          world by joining an early stage startup as the 3rd employee, building an options robo-advisor that managed
          strategies and helped users select the ideal strategy for their situation. The process taught me a lot about individual ownership,
          product-market fit, and what goes into maintaining a real business that serves customers and must remain compliant with
          strict financial regulations.
      </p>
      <p>
        Following that experience, I worked in another startup environment, this time in healthcare with
                  a more mature and funded team as the 1st/2nd engineer hired after the CTO (me and another Dev started on the same day). I
                  grew a lot as a developer and got to work alongside a very talented and hardworking team that delivered great value and insights
                  for clinical tral enrollment. Seeing what great software building processes looked like help me always work
                  towards what it best, even if it wasn't easy.
      </p>

      <h2>What I lead today</h2>
      <p>
        At Railinc, I lead Dev teams on software projects impacting the freight rail industry. The work is
        about pairing technical depth with delivery discipline: scoping
        ambiguous problems with stakeholders, breaking work down into
        shippable milestones, and unblocking the engineers doing the
        building. I still write code when needed and love to stay in the weeds with technical conversations.
         My main job is making sure the team has the room and the clarity to do their best work and that we delight the customer.
      </p>
      <p>
          I am finding that I truly enjoy this type of role, as it allows me to pait the bigger picture while ensuring the minute
          details are handled elegantly. Management is certainly a different role than being an IC Software Engineer, but having
          that background is critical to understanding the problem space well. I am constantly growing as a leader and seek
          out big opportunities to push the limits on what I can do.
        </p>

      <h2>What I'm working towards</h2>
      <p>
        Two things, mostly. The first is getting better at the parts of
        management that don't show up in any handbook. The conversations
        that change the trajectory of someone's career. Understanding how to get
        the best out of my team while keeping everyone's headspace in the right place.
        Making space for the deep work that gets crowded out by
        everything else.
      </p>
      <p>
        The second is leverage. The early years of management are about
        doing the work alongside the team. The next chapter is about
        building the conditions where good work happens without me in
        the room. The modern tools we have at our disposal should allow for
        greater leverage than we've seen in quite some time. My main goal is ship
        software that I will be proud of for decades to come while enjoying the ride at
        the same time.
      </p>

      <h2>Off the clock</h2>
      <p>
        Outside of work: weightlifting, trying to squeeze in a round of golf with the boys, cheering on the Carolina
        Panthers, Hurricanes, Charlotte Hornets and UNC. Live concerts and generally getting outdoors.
         Carolina roots that run deep.
      </p>
    </Prose>
  </section>

  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 sm:px-8 mt-20">
    <h2 class="font-display text-3xl tracking-tight mb-6">Experience</h2>
    <ul class="border-t hairline">
      {
        experience.map((job) => (
          <li class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-[1fr_auto] gap-x-8 gap-y-1 py-5 border-b hairline">
            <div>
              <p class="font-display text-lg leading-snug">{job.role}</p>
              <p class="text-coal/70 dark:text-bone-dim/70">{job.company}</p>
            </div>
            <div class="font-mono text-xs text-coal/60 dark:text-bone-dim/60 sm:text-right sm:pt-1.5 space-y-0.5">
              <p>{job.period}</p>
              {job.location && <p>{job.location}</p>}
            </div>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 sm:px-8 mt-20">
    <h2 class="font-display text-3xl tracking-tight mb-6">Certifications</h2>
    <ul class="border-t hairline pt-6 space-y-3 text-coal/80 dark:text-bone-dim/80">
      {
        certifications.map((cert) => (
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-rust dark:text-rust-bright shrink-0" aria-hidden="true">
              ▸
            </span>
            <span>{cert}</span>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </section>
</Layout>
